Comment: It's an interesting game I played some time ago actually. Once players start to realize that the queen is worth a limited amount of wood(minor pieces/rooks) their evaluation of that piece drop significantly. However, the queen can still dominate the pieces in many occasions. It happens when the greater number of pieces cannot coordinate.

I've actually seen this player use this setup in his other games. One big problem many players have is that they play the same opening setup against all openings, even if it is not optimal. I remember that I used to always do the King's Indian Setup, without thinking about the opponent. It's a horrible mistake many players make.

Bringing the queen out so early is usually not the best idea. Here it is definitely not best. White easily could have played Nf3, which is definitely going to be played at some point.

White is making already 4 pawn moves out of his 5, and is playing this opening kind of like a sicilian Kan variation. The unfortunate thiing is that black has the extra space in the center, and has contact between the pawns, so the pawn structure is dynamic and black can open it at the right moment. Since white has broken the principles of the opening, black can also do it if he wants.

(!)If you check out most of my annotations, I almost NEVER give exclamations to moves even if they are very good. However, I was very proud to discover this move, and the idea behind it. It simply looks like a blunder at first sight, since white can gain material, getting of the 2 rooks for queen. However,black has a strong idea in mind. Definitely an exclamation.
